From desj@CS.Princeton.EDU  Fri Nov 29 13:11:49 1996
Received: (from smtp@localhost) by rt.com
	id NAA18305 for <skrenta@rt.com>; Fri, 29 Nov 1996 13:11:49 -0800
Received: from cs.princeton.edu(128.112.136.10) by rt.com via smtp (V1.3)
	id sma018299; Fri Nov 29 13:11:45 1996
Received: from hart.CS.Princeton.EDU (hart [128.112.168.6]) by CS.Princeton.EDU (8.7.6/8.7.3) with SMTP id QAA15018; Fri, 29 Nov 1996 16:11:44 -0500 (EST)
Received: by hart.CS.Princeton.EDU (8.6.12/CS-Client)
        id QAA13051; Fri, 29 Nov 1996 16:11:42 -0500
Date: Fri, 29 Nov 1996 16:11:42 -0500
Message-Id: <199611292111.QAA13051@hart.CS.Princeton.EDU>
From: David desJardins <desj@CS.Princeton.EDU>
To: skrenta@rt.com
In-reply-to: <199611292033.MAA17771@rt.com> (skrenta@rt.com)
Subject: Re: oly g2 stuff
Status: OR

> Yes, that is what I was thinking of too, except "city" instead of
> "castle".  You had mentioned a concept about "increasing the amount of
> land controlled", which in some sense worried me.  If by that you mean
> something along the lines of "City X has 130 farms, walls made of
> stone 10 feet high and 3 feet thick, a well-paid & high morale
> garrison manning the walls & gate, a new sewer system, and 10
> storehouses full of grain", then I know how to implement that.  But if
> you mean that squares next to the city on the map become associated
> with the city somehow...  well then say a bit more about how that
> would work.

Sure.  The model in my head is that as you improve your castle, grow and
train your army, and perhaps "civilize" the surrounding countryside, you
could expand the area around your castle that you effectively "control."
What control means is that people in those areas consider you their
ruler, more or less.  You would get a certain amount of tax and tithe
income from provinces within your area of control; also the available
troops for your army would be limited to a fraction of the population
under your control (and you would have to pay them as well); you would
get reports on activities in such areas; you could employ the workforce
in such areas to exploit locally occurring natural resources; etc.

You could have a simpler or a more complex model.  A simple model would
perhaps be something like Oly g2 castle "levels": improving your castle
to the next level would increase the area around it that you could
control.  There could also be other necessary conditions: e.g., no
unfriendly forces in those areas, an army of a certain size and strength
to project power over such an area.

A more complex model might have "loyalty" ratings for individual
provinces: provinces nearer to your castle would have higher natural
loyalty; loyalty could be raised by investment in the province
infrastructure, giving out food and so forth, stationing troops to
impose martial law.  Loyalty would fall with unfavorable economic
events; excessive taxation; enemy action.  So your ability to draw
resources from the area would depend on your investment in its loyalty.
This would be a more complex economic game than the previous.

> Actually having both would be good.  The more dimensions it's possible
> to improve in, the better.  And having squares around a city that could
> be picked off would be good, since there will be a natural tendency to
> run into the land of your neighbor as you expand.  But I wouldn't want
> that to be the only vector of growth for cities.  I think there should be
> lots of internal stats that a city king can raise.

It seems to me you can have both.  You can try to develop a city into an
economic or military powerhouse, but you might be dependent on outside
sources of food and raw materials, or you could try to control a large
agrarian economy but you might be lacking in skilled tradesmen and the
like.  Also, all economies might depend to some extent on outside trade
(plains communities need metal from mountain mines, etc.).

I see castles (the player-controlled or npc-controlled pov's that
control territory) as independent from cities, as in Oly.  Although
there would be obvious advantages to putting your castle in a city.

I think of the game as initially starting with a small civilized area
and a large (infinite?) uncivilized wilderness which might not have any
cities.  In order to develop such a wilderness you would have to
civilize it (wipe out the "orcs"); then the human population
("citizens") would gradually grow and develop the land.

> What would happen if you tried to subjugate a nearby square that contained
> a separate city?  I think that a player POV should be required to run
> each city, so one player can't glob all the cities on the map together
> and run them as one big empire.

In my model there is an increasing difficulty of controlling a larger
and larger area from a single location/pov.  The effective maximum
radius depends on scale but perhaps a radius of 6 Oly provinces or so.
Past that point effective control would either be impossible (in the
simple model) or extremely expensive to maintain (in the complex
"loyalty" model).

> I was thinking about the issue you raised about being able to see
> an army coming in enough time to do something about it.   I was
> thinking that the map could be constructed so that a cities would
> appear spaced 3-6 squares apart.  Lone nobles could travel up to
> 3 or so squares in a single hop per update.  Armies could move 1
> square per update.

> This give city owners at least N updates to see armies coming (where
> N is the number of non-city squares between them and the nearest
> city) to see armies coming, but lets nobles travel about the map
> quickly.  Some noble activity may be heavily city oriented, such
> as trade, and I don't think traders should have to spend 3/4 of
> their time stuck in the wilderness just moving between trade
> opportunities.

This all seems ok.  I'm not so worried about speed of movement in this
model, because most of your  power comes from your "castle", and that's
where most really significant combat will occur.  There won't be a whole
lot of maneuvering to intercept armies in the plains (which is good).

No time now to comment on the map stuff.  Later.

                                        David desJardins

