Rich,

> > That cap isn't in the mark 2 changes, did you change your mind?
> 
> View the g2-changes web page, it always has the latest revision.
> 

Right, though I notice the weights of knightoids are still wrong.

> I agree that self-balancing systems are great, but I don't have
> much experience implementing them, and they're of course considerably
> more complicated to implement.  I'll give it some thought though.
> Any suggestions for specific parameter modification algorithms?

Maybe more complicated in a coding sense, but often easier from the
design point of view than working out the correct constants once and
for all before starting the game.

On the breeding example, it would be too fiddly to change the time to
breed each species adaptively, but the 20% risk could easily be wobbled
up by, say, 0.01% for each breeding attempt, with the risks for all
species then reduced by an equal amount to bring the average back to
about 20%. The numbers could be published each turn or hidden according
to taste, but either would tend to lead to more mixed armies than the
constant numbers that inevitably get "solved".

The trade example is harder because of all the hyperspace options making
it hard to distinguish a long route from a short route. It may be that
trade would have a better feel if it was somehow encouraged or forced to
stay in the normal world rather than being another advantage of controlling
the weird places. Would it be good to populate Faerie and Hades with
mischievous leprechauns and imps that steal some proportion of trade
goods passing through? It might help preserve their fantasy feel rather
than making them commercial highways.

If you did that, it would be practical to relate trade good price
differentials to real-world distance, though proper floating markets
would be the only way to get perfect results...

				Jeremy



