My turn :)

I waited for all of you to finish speaking, such a polite boy I am.

1.  I do NOT want to see priest visions eliminated.  For 1 NP, what's
	the purpose of having one?  Ressurect Dead Nobles who come back
	at reduced strength?  Last Rites (new version, of course) to get
	the NPs back faster?  The Olympian Gods are not very powerful.
	Why cannot a Priest Bless a region like a Mage can do common
	works for $100?  Or curse regions?  Whatever.

Rich Skrenta wrote:
> 
> To add a bit more to the topic...
> 
> Some of the responses I've received have said that I haven't gone
> far enough.  That beast armies are still too powerful with their
> high combat values and 0 maintenance cost.  I am trying to steer
> a middle course through the possible changes; I want to leave some
> spunk in the game, but the consensus seems to be that it should be
> much harder to grow in power than in G1.

I concur that beast armies should be harder to expand than game 1.  I 
think the addition of lengthened breeding times does this.  So tell me,
how many turns will it be before someone can afford to try and CAPTURE
one?  Its going to take several turns to build up enough troops to try
and take on quest in the proper type of liar to get combat vs a dragon.
Assuming you capture 1, it will be 5 turns before you can try another
quest in the same location.  And then there's a % chance you get 
dragons.  So to capture 3 dragons, it will take, what, 75 turns?  That's
if there is only one type of sub-location where dragons can be found in
the area the player is working.  16 breeding attempts between then and
turn 100, with 5 failing, 5 causing the death of a breeder, all that
effort so by turn 100 you have 9 dragons....
unless you breed Giant Birds and Giant Lizards or whatever that combo is
to make dragons from lesser beasts...

Hard to say.
 
> Remember also that everyone will be playing with the same limits.
> Perhaps the changes seem daunting if you imagine yourself coming
> up against G1 adversaries, but in G2, the slower growth will apply
> equally to all players.
> 
> And finally, we already have a G1 with G1 rules.  If players want
> something bloodier than G2, perhaps a reset G1 with a few changes,
> or perhaps an even bloodier game with some closed-ended victory
> conditions, that's always a possibility.  (Actually I was toying
> with the idea of repackaging Olympia I as a closed-ended wargame;
> it's a disaster in terms of open-ended balance, but it's got a
> great exponetial ramp-up, and the mechanics are sufficiently
> different that Olympia II to make it seem like another game entirely.)

I would not play a closed-ended "victory is possible" Olympia.  I play 
these games to meet new people, explore, fight NPCs, and occasionally,
kick some deserving player's butt.  Let game 1 continue while game 2
goes on.  People who want more "bloodiness" can play game 1.  My only
concern is if g2 becomes too much a politically correct game...war is
unprofitable.  Also, without gatecraft, large armies will have a terrible 
time moving..6 days per hex for flying armies.  Hmm...ship travel just 
became faster.  Not as bad as I thought :)
 
> Probably better for me to spend my time writing a web-pbem or
