I tried to reply to this yesterday but my provider seems to be sliding
down hill.  I'm starting to hunt around for another ISP.  Looks like I
might be able to find full-time dial-up for under $100 per month.

>> I like this.  You may want to have the initial price seperated by a
>> certain margin and then have that margin close and the tradegood
>> ends its lifespan.

>Originally I planned to do that but I ran out of steam.

>The real question is whether 3000 gold is too little or too much
>incentive to be a trader.  This can easily be adjusted as the game
>proceeds without undue disruption however if it proves to require
>change.

Well, I'd make it a random range between, say, 2000 and 4000.  This
would give you more breathing room to quietly adjust things later
since changes would be less noticable than with a fixed value.  I
think you need to run a few sanity checks where you compare a bunch
of activities with respect to how much gold can be made in a given
time doing it moderately and optimally and shoot for balance.

>The change is CBIB with respect to combat, i.e. it applies to all
>combat, not just certain combats.

Well, I'll trust that you've fixed the problem since I didn't deal
with beasts much beyond getting eliminated by the.  See Jeremy Maiden's
comments about simulating breeding scenarios.

>Size limits are a fine idea, but 1) it would be exceptionally difficult
>to add them to the Olympia mechanics, there are all sorts of ways to
>travel which would need ugly patches or else they would present holes,
>and 2) I don't know what to make the size limits; choosing wise limits
>which are neither too large so as to be useless, or too small so as to
>make the monsters invincleable.  The slower movement and other restrictions
>on large stacks will in part address this problem; it is in general a bit
>harder to drag around a huge stack in G2.

You might want to ultimately increase it so that a single noble can
move more than 20 troops before there is a penalty but I think you are
better off starting with a lower number and raising it.  People will
complain less that way if changes are necessary.

>I also changed the configuration of Faery, it should be impossible to
>do what the AOO did with it now.

Again, I'll trust you here.  My main concern is that a faction use it
as a quick way to jump around the world, unfairly cutting off people
who travelled there conventionally.  If you feel that's been addressed,
then that's fine.

>> I'd personally limit the skills to Combat, Shipcraft, and Forestry --
>> enough to get people moving.  Maybe one other skill each for flavor.
>> I'll comment more on this below.

>Actually the list is your suggestion, verbatim, from a mail you sent
>some time ago.  :-)

OK.  This made me think about why I would have made such a suggestion.
I believe it had to do with allowing units trapped in IC ways to excape
(Stealth) and the ability to get a good start on other game activities
(Construction, etc.).  This is a little less necessary now that there
are 6 starting cities but I suppose the idea is still valid for safe
havens.

>Well, when coastal crawl was originally discovered, I got all kinds of
>gripes about how stupid it was.  Thus was lodged in my head the idea to
>fix it, which persisted on various to-do lists for 2.5 years.  Now people
>say they like it.  Well, you can go find the sea lanes.

OK.  No problem.  

[Performing common tasks for gold]
>> I would again suggest not allowing this in safe havens.

>Why?

Because the new players wind up at the bottom of the execution queue
for the city and will never be able to use it if other players have a
lock on it for whatever reason.  We went over this with G1 when I
suggested adding new players to the top of the list when they start
the game.  Remember that being first matters quite a bit for a lot of
things and, in safe havens, there is no way to push someone off.
Similarly, this is a reason to reconsider buildings in a safe haven.
If someone accidentally leaves a tower, a person higher in the
location than they are can jump in and take it from them and there is
nothing that can be done about it, unlike anyplace else where
attacking is an option.  Again, I'd suggest placing new players at the
top of the list for safe locations to give them a jump on resources
such as peasants (can you recruit in safe havens?) because they need
it the most.  This also gives old players less incentive to stick
around and constantly be pushed down the list.  It will also give new
players a comodity to deal with when allying with older players (list
position).

Another artifact you might want is some sort of scepter that allows
the holder (and only the holder) to attack in safe-havens.  Since
there are six and I suspect that they are some distance apart, this
wouldn't shut out new players if a single city is dangerous.  It might
help shake things up if they get stagnant.  You'd just have to make
sure that the holder would have to walk from city to city and couldn't
jump around to all the save havens in a turn or two.  Perhaps an
automatic announcement in the safe havens of the artifact, it's holder,
and it's holder's location would help, too, when it is discovered.

>> I can see good reasons why a faction with no chance of recovering the
>> body (e.g. a noble lost exploring though Faery or such) might want the
>> wait to be *less*.

>Yes, that's why it's longer.

Then the player will undergo sufficient punishment for the death of an
unrecovered body and you should consider dropping the 1 NP penalty for
resurrections since (A) the player will already have wasted time and
effort on it and (B) the noble suffers some loses in the process.
BTW, I'd change the loss from Defense (recoverable via a skill) to
Health -- perhaps 20 or 25 points -- and consider the character as
having been wounded by the resurrection with respect to the healing or
dying check if that is still in there.  Make the reduced number the
new maximum.  This would give all nobles 4 or 5 resurrections before
they are dead-dead.  Perhaps an artifact could restore a noble's youth
once per game year or something.

[Restocking monsters]
>> I'd adjust the wait from 3-5 to 3-8 turns -- mabye longer.

>Okay.

My fear is that a player will be able to predict the restocking
and revisit a series of nearby lairs in sequence, constantly finding
something there.  Adjust accordingly.

>> I think that only Combat should be a given since it is needed to train
>> protection.  Stealth and Magic should be optional.

>Again, this was based heavily on your suggestions.  Please be
>consistent.  :-)

Well, bear in mind that my original suggestions were made in the context
of a single starting city and one can change their mind.  :-)

In retrospect, there are reasons why I would have suggested
well-stocked safe havens -- specifically for later in the game when
all the surrounding areas will be well colonized. 

>> The key things that this plan tries to achieve is to differentiate
>> the cities, to encourage travel to learn new skills, and to add some
>> flavor, in general, the learning proces.

>I'm not going to solve the lack-of-flavor problem in Olympia easily.

Yes, but every little bit helps.

>Skill distribution for regional skills is already regional.  Given that
>one needs to spend exactly 1 day in a city to pick up a skill, I don't
>think much atmosphere will be gained from spreading skills around.

I disagree.  It makes it more important if you are in city X than city
Y if X teaches something that you want and Y doesn't.  If they are both
the same, they are interchangable.  Anything that makes it important 
that you be in a particular place adds flavor to the geography.

>> I'm interested in why you feel that cities should have so many skills.
>> The only reason I can see for having so many skills is to cater to the
>> "I don't want to work to do that" crowd.  Is there another reason?

>To prevent powerful factions from hording lone cities which supply skills.

OK.  Here is a revised formula plus some reasoning where it differs
from your plan.

o  Every city teaches Combat (since you need combat to build troops)
   and Construction (needed to build towers and such -- how a city
   gets built up so it makes sense).

o  Each city teaches a regional skill (Beastmastery in plains and
   swamps [I suspect it will still be a much desired skill], Mining in
   mountains, Forestry in forests, and Trading in deserts [how do you
   think they maintain cities in the desert, huh? :->].  Any port
   city will also teach Shipcraft in addition to any regional skill
   indicated by the terrain outside of the city.  The six starting
   safe havens should be divided between all five terrains with the
   last city also being a forest city (basically, 2 Beastmastery, 
   1 Trading, 1 Mining, and 2 Forestry cities). 

o  Each city teaches a dark or subversive skill -- either Stealth
   (50%), Persuasion (45%), or Necromancy (5%).  Exactly which of these
   skills a city teaches will remain hidden until discovered by an
   EXPLORE that turns it up.  This will allow for quests to find
   Necromancy.  Safe havens will only have Stealth.  The idea is that
   the underground of each city operates by one of these means and
   you need to find it get get training in it.  Vary the percentages
   to suit your tastes.  

o  Each city will teach one magic skill -- Magic, Alchemy, Gatecraft,
   Weather Magic, Scrying, or Artifact Construction.  Since that is
   6 magics, you divide them between the six starting safe havens,
   one each, and then randomly everywhere else.  This will add some
   flavor the the starting selections.

Where this differs from your plan is that Shipcraft is an extra and
Forestry isn't guaranteed to starting players.  Magic is just another
Magic and players can pick which magic they might want to start with
by picking their starting city.  Finally, I think that obscuring Stealth,
Persuasion, and Necromancy might add some flavor and hint that these
are potentially troubling skills.  It makes people have to really work
to find them.

>> I can probably think up more if you think I'm on the right track.

>Some of these are cool, I will see what I have time to implement.

What other types of things are you looking for?  To use the board-game
_Cosmic Encounters_ as an example, special abilities are good if they
let you break or bend one game rule.  Alternately, they could provide
an easier to use version of an existing game item.  Keeping that in
mind, you should be able to think of quite a few of these things.

>The primary limit are the beastmastery changes, no one will have big
>dragon armies in g2, it takes almost three turns to make a single
>dragon.

I wasn't a beast person so I'll trust that those who were will sanity
check this.

>> Is this really a good thing?  I can see the safe havens becomming 
>> shanty towns of towers.  I really think you should encourage people
>> to move around.  What is the reason behind this?

>To add color to cities.  :-)

OK.  But see my above comments.

John Morrow




