Rich,

> > On sea-land movement: it now costs 8 days to land in forest? This
> > makes exploring by sea drastically less appealing than before, assuming
> > the map is still secret. (I agree the one day coastal crawl business
> > was daft, but this seems an extreme reaction)
> 
> Many people seem to have come out in defense of "coastal crawl", perhaps
> I will simply put it back in.
> 

But it's horrid! The 8 days to land in forest would be OK if it was on
purpose, ie the facilities at a port allow a 1 day landing in a city but
finding a beach and debarquing is difficult. How about different commands
to sail to sea and land? Ie you could explore the sea by writing

sail n e s w

and if there's land in one of those directions the sail fails because
you should have written

land n e s w

to get ashore. People who really want to get the old random landings and
launchings could alternate SAIL and LAND.

> > Only allowing 10 men per noble prevents any
> > mobile stack being big enough to take on even modest beast armies,
> > maybe not even the NPC monsters. It would be _really_ nice to have
> > viable human armies   :-)
> 
> The penalty is not a strict limit at 1:10, but a gradual penalty
> designed to make it hard to move big armies around.
> 

Yes, but it becomes a blocking hard limit very quickly, eg moving a workforce
of 150 into a mountain for castle building takes 29 days. It's worse for
armies: even if you used the new cheap horses to make your army entirely
riding speed it would be down to less than one square per turn movement at
300 men. OK, multiple nobles would help, but it's hard to see people using
human armies that take up lots of nobles and even then can't keep up with
land-based beast armies.

If the gradual penalty is a good thing, why not apply it to beasts as well?

				Jeremy

