> > 10) I'm not so sure about Trances. A mage without auraculum takes
> > forever to recharge. That's a bit too slow, and trances (28 days) are
> > a bit fast. You can do this by tweaking the numbers in Meditation and
> > Trances.
> 
> How about 40 days for a trance?

Yes, and/or you could make a trance restore only up to 1/2 or 2/3 of
your max aura. I think I like 28 days up to a max of 2/3 of your aura
(i.e. no matter where you are when you start the trance, you end at
2/3 max).

And in case I wasn't clear I think that mages without Advanced Sorcery
should also have Trance available. It's too important and too good to
be limited to super mages only.  You could fix this by making
meditation and advanced meditation better. For example, meditation
could give you 1 aura point or 5% of your max aura, whichever is
larger. Advanced meditation would be 2 aura points or 10% of your max
aura, whichever is larger. I have a mage with 40 max aura who could
auraculate now... advanced meditation would get her 4 points/week, or
she could spend 28 days on a trance and get back 26 points (2/3),
which is just over 6 points a week. Yes, that's a nice gradual
increase in capability as you get stronger.

-- g


From lindahl@rt.com  Tue Oct 29 01:28:57 1996
Received: (from lindahl@localhost) by rt.com
	id BAA22036 for skrenta; Tue, 29 Oct 1996 01:28:57 -0500
Message-Id: <199610290628.BAA22036@rt.com>
Subject: speaking of g2
To: skrenta (Rich Skrenta)
Date: Tue, 29 Oct 1996 01:28:57 -0500 (EST)
From: "Greg Lindahl" <lindahl@pbm.com>
X-Mailer: ELM [version 2.4 PL25]
Content-Type: text
Content-Length: 882       
Status: OR

After talking to Steve Chapin a bit, I'm convinced that Noble Points
should be strictly conserved: never destroyed, never created except 1
per 8 turns. He convinced me by pointing out that the AOO players are
all giving Barry their NPs as they drop, and with the scheme I
proposed to you a while back, he could do the same thing and simply go
way negative on NPs.

Of course, you didn't respond to that scheme, which is generally a bad
sign ;-) Making NPs strictly conserved means a little extra code when
a body decays; you would also want a DISCARD id command if you want to
kill off a noble to recover the NPs. So after you terrorize the
prisoner, you have to have NPs available or they won't swear to
you. When you decide that they're a waste of NPs, you just discard
them. Contract nobles are still bad because they eat your gold and the
enemy can capture their skills.

-- g


